# Legal Reference Template

This template defines the standard structure for each BOL power's legal reference entry. Every power from Article V, Section 2 (a-ccc) gets one file following this format.

---

## File Naming Convention

`{NN}-{letter}-{short-slug}.md` — numbered sequentially following Art. V, Sec. 2 order (a=01 through ccc=55).

Examples: `01-a-administration-of-justice.md`, `34-bb-health.md`, `31-aa-hajj-and-umrah.md`

Full numbering:
01-a, 02-b, 03-c, 04-d, 05-e, 06-f, 07-g, 08-h, 09-i, 10-j,
11-k, 12-l, 13-m, 14-n, 15-o, 16-p, 17-q, 18-r, 19-s, 20-t,
21-u, 22-v, 23-w, 24-x, 25-y, 26-z, 27-aa, 28-bb, 29-cc, 30-dd,
31-ee, 32-ff, 33-gg, 34-hh, 35-ii, 36-jj, 37-kk, 38-ll, 39-mm, 40-nn,
41-oo, 42-pp, 43-qq, 44-rr, 45-ss, 46-tt, 47-uu, 48-vv, 49-ww, 50-xx,
51-yy, 52-zz, 53-aaa, 54-bbb, 55-ccc

---

## Quick Conformance Check

Before submitting a power file, verify:
- [ ] File named `{NN}-{letter}-{slug}.md` (e.g., `01-a-administration-of-justice.md`)
- [ ] Legal Briefer present with all 5 subsections — 800-1,500 words, answers 20 guide questions
- [ ] BOL Provisions table: ALL provisions listed with verbatim text + explanation/implication
- [ ] Bangsamoro Legislation (BAAs): uses PB No. column (not "Bill No." or "Enacted Bills")
- [ ] Parliamentary Resolutions: uses PR No. column
- [ ] National Laws: comprehensive enumeration (not just BOL-cited laws)
- [ ] Jurisprudence: relevant SC decisions listed (or "none identified" stated)
- [ ] Parliament Bills (Pending): filed PBs listed BEFORE Legislative Gaps
- [ ] Legislative Gaps: Type A gaps name the BAA 13 ministry
- [ ] Zero instances of "Exclusive", "Shared", or "Concurrent" as power labels
- [ ] All BAA numbers verified against `legislation/baas/BAA-{N}.md`
- [ ] Feliciano citation format in Footnotes

---

## Template Structure

```markdown
# (x) [Power Name as stated in BOL]

> **BOL Art. V, Sec. 2({letter})** — "[Verbatim text from BOL]"

## Power Overview

| Attribute | Value |
|-----------|-------|
| **BOL Basis** | Art. V, Sec. 2({letter}) — enumerated power |
| **National Law Consistency Required** | Yes (cite BOL provision) / No / Intergovernmental coordination (cite Art. VI body) |
| **Lead Ministry/Office** | [From BAA No. 85 and BAA No. 13] |
| **Supporting Agencies** | [Other BARMM bodies with jurisdiction] |
| **BDP Chapter(s)** | [BDP 2023-2028 chapter alignment] |
| **Priority Code** | [If covered by a priority code, e.g., Administrative Code, Education Code] |

## Legal Briefer

This is the primary content of each legal reference — a comprehensive narrative that tells you everything you need to know about this power's legal landscape. The detailed tables that follow are supporting reference data.

### What This Power Covers
[2-3 paragraphs: What the BOL means by this power. Start with the verbatim Art. V Sec. 2 grant, then explain the full scope by walking through every other BOL provision that elaborates on it (Art. VI through XVIII). What bodies does the BOL create for this power? What does the BOL require the Parliament to enact? What limits does it set? Write as if explaining to someone who has never read the BOL but needs to understand this subject area completely.]

### How the Bangsamoro Government Exercises This Power Today
[2-3 paragraphs: The current state of implementation. Which ministry or office leads (from BAA 13 and BAA 85), and what their mandate covers. Name every standalone BAA that has been enacted for this power, with what each one does. If the power is exercised only through a BAA 13 mandate without standalone legislation, explain what the ministry can and cannot do under that general mandate alone. Mention any relevant parliamentary resolutions that signal Parliament's intent.]

### How National Law Interacts with This Power
[1-2 paragraphs: The relationship between Bangsamoro and national authority for this power. If the BOL requires consistency with national law, cite the specific provision and name the national law (RA, EO, PD). If the BOL creates an intergovernmental body for this area (Art. VI), name it and explain its role. If no national law consistency is required but national law applies suppletorily because no BAA has been enacted yet, name the suppletory national law and explain what happens when a BAA is eventually passed. If the BOL requires Presidential approval or national government coordination, explain the mechanism.]

### What Is Missing — Gaps and Legislative Opportunities
[2-3 paragraphs: The most important section for legislators and planners. What standalone legislation does this power need that doesn't exist yet? What would a dedicated BAA codify — standards, regulatory framework, institutional structure, funding mechanisms — that BAA 13's general mandate doesn't cover? Are there BOL mandates (e.g., "The Parliament shall enact...") that remain unfulfilled? Are there unresolved national law interactions — areas where the BOL and national law potentially overlap and no mechanism clarifies which governs? Name specific bill concepts and what they would accomplish.]

### Development and Policy Connection
[1-2 paragraphs: How this power connects to the Bangsamoro Development Plan (BDP 2023-2028) and the Mas Matatag na Bangsamoro Agenda (2026-2028). Which BDP chapter and goals depend on the exercise of this power? Which of the 5 Matatag pillars does this power support? What development outcomes are at stake if the legislative gaps are not addressed?]

---

